-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LUKE CHAPTER 4 — The Temptation and the Beginning of the Galilean Ministry
-- 44 verses · Greek text · Word studies · Cross-refs
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- Step 1: Insert chapter metadata
INSERT INTO chapters (book_id, chapter_number, overview, theme, key_word_original, key_word_meaning, outline)
SELECT b.id, 4,
  'Luke 4 narrates three pivotal events that define the nature and scope of Jesus''s messianic mission. The Temptation in the Wilderness (vv.1-13) portrays Jesus, filled with the Holy Spirit, being led into the desert for forty days of satanic testing. Three temptations target appetite, authority, and divine protection; Jesus answers each with Deuteronomy, refusing to acquire the kingdom by any path other than obedience to the Father. Satan departs ''for a season'' (v.13), planning a more opportune time (cf. 22:3). The Rejection at Nazareth (vv.14-30) provides the programmatic declaration of Jesus''s mission: reading from Isaiah 61 in the synagogue, he announces ''The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he hath anointed me to preach the gospel to the poor... to set at liberty them that are bruised'' (vv.18-19), and then declares ''This day is this scripture fulfilled in your ears'' (v.21). When Jesus implies that Gentiles would receive what Israel rejected (the examples of Elijah and Elisha), the Nazareth congregation attempts to kill him (vv.28-30). This rejection of his hometown anticipates the wider rejection by Israel. The Galilean Ministry (vv.31-44) begins with power: exorcism in the Capernaum synagogue (vv.31-37), the healing of Simon''s mother-in-law (vv.38-39), and a mass healing at sunset (vv.40-41). When the demonic cry of recognition disturbs the synagogue, Jesus silences it — consistently refusing to allow demons to proclaim his identity. The chapter closes with Jesus withdrawing to pray before declaring his universal mission: ''I must preach the kingdom of God to other cities also: for therefore am I sent'' (v.43).',
  'The Anointed One — Withstanding Temptation and Proclaiming the Jubilee of the Spirit',
  'δεῖ (dei)',
  'It is necessary, one must, it is divinely required — from the impersonal verb from deō (to bind). The word expresses divine compulsion, the inescapable necessity of God''s redemptive plan. In Luke 4:43: ''I must preach the kingdom of God to other cities also: for therefore am I sent'' — the dei of mission. Throughout Luke, dei marks the non-negotiable elements of Jesus''s vocation: he must suffer (9:22; 17:25; 24:7), be crucified (24:26), rise again (24:26), and ascend (Acts 1:11). In chapter 4, the dei is implicit in the temptation (he must resist every shortcut to the kingdom) and explicit in the mission statement (he must go to other cities). Jesus lives under divine compulsion — not external coercion but the inner necessity of love and obedience to the Father''s redemptive plan.',
  '["The Temptation of Jesus (vv.1-13): Jesus being full of the Holy Ghost returned from Jordan and was led by the Spirit into the wilderness being forty days tempted of the devil. The devil said — If thou be the Son of God command this stone to be made bread. Jesus answered — It is written Man shall not live by bread alone. The devil took him up and showed him all the kingdoms of the world in a moment of time and said — All this power will I give thee if thou wilt worship me. Jesus answered — It is written Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God and him only shalt thou serve. The devil set him on a pinnacle of the temple and said — If thou be the Son of God cast thyself down for he shall give his angels charge over thee. Jesus answered — Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God. The devil departed from him for a season","The Rejection at Nazareth (vv.14-30): Jesus returned in the power of the Spirit into Galilee. He came to Nazareth where he had been brought up and went into the synagogue on the sabbath day and stood up to read. There was delivered to him the book of Esaias. He found the place where it was written — The Spirit of the Lord is upon me because he hath anointed me to preach the gospel to the poor he hath sent me to heal the brokenhearted to preach deliverance to the captives and recovery of sight to the blind to set at liberty them that are bruised to preach the acceptable year of the Lord. He closed the book and said — This day is this scripture fulfilled in your ears. They said — Is not this Joseph''s son? He said — No prophet is accepted in his own country. He cited Elijah sent to a Gentile widow and Elisha healing Naaman the Syrian. All in the synagogue were filled with wrath and thrust him out and led him to a cliff to throw him down but he passing through the midst of them went his way","The Capernaum Ministry (vv.31-44): He came to Capernaum and taught on the sabbath. In the synagogue was a man with an unclean spirit who cried out — Let us alone what have we to do with thee Jesus of Nazareth art thou come to destroy us? I know thee who thou art the Holy One of God. Jesus rebuked him — Hold thy peace and come out of him. And he came out. The people were all amazed. He arose out of the synagogue and entered Simon''s house and his wife''s mother was sick of a great fever. Jesus stood over her and rebuked the fever and it left her. When the sun was setting all they that had any sick with divers diseases brought them and he laid his hands on every one of them and healed them. Devils also came out of many crying — Thou art Christ the Son of God. He rebuking suffered them not to speak for they knew he was Christ. When it was day he departed and went into a desert place. The people sought him and said — Stay with us. He said — I must preach the kingdom of God to other cities also for therefore am I sent. And he preached in the synagogues of Galilee"]'
FROM books b WHERE b.name = 'Luke';

-- Step 2: Insert all 44 verses
INSERT INTO verses (chapter_id, verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
SELECT c.id, v.verse_number, v.kjv_text, v.original_text, v.transliteration, v.study_note, v.doctrinal_note
FROM chapters c
JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'And Jesus being full of the Holy Ghost returned from Jordan, and was led by the Spirit into the wilderness,',
   'Ἰησοῦς δὲ πλήρης Πνεύματος Ἁγίου ὑπέστρεψεν ἀπὸ τοῦ Ἰορδάνου καὶ ἤγετο ἐν τῷ Πνεύματι ἐν τῇ ἐρήμῳ',
   'Iēsous de plērēs Pneumatos Hagiou hypestrepsen apo tou Iordanou kai ēgeto en tō Pneumati en tē erēmō',
   '''Full of the Holy Ghost'' (plērēs Pneumatos Hagiou — full of the Holy Spirit; the same Spirit that descended at the baptism now fills Jesus). Luke emphasises the Spirit''s role throughout the temptation: Jesus is led by the Spirit (v.1), returns in the power of the Spirit (v.14), and reads the Spirit-anointed Isaiah passage in the synagogue (v.18). The Spirit does not protect Jesus from temptation but leads him into it — the testing is a necessary precondition for the public ministry. ''Was led'' (ēgeto — was being led; imperfect passive, indicating the Spirit''s continuous guidance throughout the wilderness period). The wilderness (erēmos) echoes Israel''s forty years of testing in the desert — Jesus succeeds where Israel failed.',
   NULL),
  (2, 'Being forty days tempted of the devil. And in those days he did eat nothing: and when they were ended, he afterward hungered.',
   'ἡμέρας τεσσεράκοντα πειραζόμενος ὑπὸ τοῦ διαβόλου καὶ οὐκ ἔφαγεν οὐδὲν ἐν ταῖς ἡμέραις ἐκείναις καὶ συντελεσθεισῶν αὐτῶν ἐπείνασεν',
   'hēmeras tesserakonta peirazomenos hypo tou diabolou kai ouk ephagen ouden en tais hēmerais ekeinais kai syntelestheisōn autōn epeinasen',
   '''Forty days'' (hēmeras tesserakonta — forty days; cf. Moses: Exodus 24:18; 34:28 — forty days on Sinai without food; Elijah: 1 Kings 19:8 — forty days to Horeb). The forty days identify Jesus with the great mediators of Israel. ''Tempted'' (peirazomenos — being tested, tried; peirazomai = to test, examine, tempt; the word can mean either genuine testing for the purpose of proof or enticement to sin; here both meanings apply: the devil seeks to lead to sin; God uses it to demonstrate the Son''s faithfulness). ''He afterward hungered'' (epeinasen — he was hungry; aorist: the acute hunger came at the end of the fast, when his human body reached its physical limits — the precise moment of maximum vulnerability for the first temptation).',
   NULL),
  (3, 'And the devil said unto him, If thou be the Son of God, command this stone that it be made bread.',
   'εἶπεν δὲ αὐτῷ ὁ διάβολος Εἰ υἱὸς εἶ τοῦ θεοῦ εἰπὲ τῷ λίθῳ τούτῳ ἵνα γένηται ἄρτος',
   'eipen de autō ho diabolos Ei huios ei tou theou eipe tō lithō toutō hina genētai artos',
   '''If thou be the Son of God'' (Ei huios ei tou theou — if you are the Son of God; the ''if'' is not a statement of doubt but a conditional: ''Since you are...then prove it by...''; or possibly a genuine test of whether Jesus will use his divine power for himself). The devil has just heard the Father''s declaration ''Thou art my beloved Son'' (3:22); his first temptation targets that identity. ''Command this stone to be made bread'' — a miracle within Jesus''s power, to meet a genuine need (hunger after forty days). The temptation is not to do something obviously evil but to do something good (feeding himself) by the wrong means (using his divine power for self-preservation rather than in obedience to the Father''s leading). The issue is not whether he can but whether he should.',
   NULL),
  (4, 'And Jesus answered him, saying, It is written, That man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word of God.',
   'καὶ ἀπεκρίθη Ἰησοῦς πρὸς αὐτόν γέγραπται ὅτι Οὐκ ἐπ᾽ ἄρτῳ μόνῳ ζήσεται ὁ ἄνθρωπος',
   'kai apekrithē Iēsous pros auton gegraptai hoti Ouk ep artō monō zēsetai ho anthrōpos',
   '''It is written'' (gegraptai — it stands written; perfect passive: permanently written, always applicable). Jesus quotes Deuteronomy 8:3 — God''s explanation to Israel of why he let them hunger in the wilderness (so they would learn to trust his word). ''Man shall not live by bread alone'' (Ouk ep artō monō zēsetai ho anthrōpos) — life in its fullest sense (zōē) is sustained not by physical nutrition but by every word (rhēmati) proceeding from God''s mouth. Jesus refuses to act independently of the Father''s word. Where Israel murmured at the lack of bread (Exodus 16), Jesus trusts the God who provides. He cites the lesson Israel was supposed to learn from the wilderness but failed to — and he himself lives it. All three of Jesus''s answers come from Deuteronomy (6-8), the section dealing with Israel''s wilderness testing.',
   NULL),
  (5, 'And the devil, taking him up into an high mountain, shewed unto him all the kingdoms of the world in a moment of time.',
   'Καὶ ἀναγαγὼν αὐτὸν ὁ διάβολος εἰς ὄρος ὑψηλὸν ἔδειξεν αὐτῷ πάσας τὰς βασιλείας τῆς οἰκουμένης ἐν στιγμῇ χρόνου',
   'Kai anagagōn auton ho diabolos eis oros hypsēlon edeixsen autō pasas tas basileias tēs oikoumenēs en stigmē chronou',
   '''All the kingdoms of the world in a moment of time'' (pasas tas basileias tēs oikoumenēs en stigmē chronou — all the kingdoms of the inhabited world in a point/instant of time; stigmē = a point, an instant; the Greek root of our word ''stigma''). The vision is supernatural, a panoramic spiritual display. The second temptation is the greatest in scope: all political power and authority over the entire inhabited world. ''In a moment of time'' implies a vision beyond natural sight — either a spiritual experience or a demonic projection. The kingdoms of the world are the Messiah''s by right (Psalm 2:8: ''Ask of me, and I shall give thee the heathen for thine inheritance, and the uttermost parts of the earth for thy possession'') — but the devil offers to shortcut the cross and give them now, by a different path.',
   NULL),
  (6, 'And the devil said unto him, All this power will I give thee, and the glory of them: for that is delivered unto me; and to whomsoever I will I give it.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῷ ὁ διάβολος Σοὶ δώσω τὴν ἐξουσίαν ταύτην ἅπασαν καὶ τὴν δόξαν αὐτῶν ὅτι ἐμοὶ παραδέδοται καὶ ᾧ ἂν θέλω δίδωμι αὐτήν',
   'kai eipen autō ho diabolos Soi dōsō tēn exousian tautēn hapasan kai tēn doxan autōn hoti emoi paradedotai kai hō an thelō didōmi autēn',
   '''Delivered unto me'' (emoi paradedotai — it has been handed over to me; a claim based on the Fall — Satan acquired a degree of authority over the fallen world, cf. John 12:31: ''the prince of this world''; 2 Corinthians 4:4: ''the god of this age''). The claim is partially true (Satan does have real, temporary dominion over fallen humanity) but the offer is deceptive: (1) Jesus can receive what is rightfully his (Psalm 2) only through the Father, not through Satan; (2) acceptance would mean worshipping Satan — an absolute inversion of the divine order; (3) the glory offered is real but temporary; the glory obtained through the cross is eternal (Philippians 2:9-11). The temptation targets political ambition — the desire to establish the kingdom by the world''s methods rather than God''s.',
   NULL),
  (7, 'If thou therefore wilt worship me, all shall be thine.',
   'σὺ οὖν ἐὰν προσκυνήσῃς ἐνώπιον ἐμοῦ ἔσται σοῦ πᾶσα',
   'sy oun ean proskynēsēs enōpion emou estai sou pasa',
   '''If thou therefore wilt worship me'' (ean proskynēsēs enōpion emou — if you will prostrate yourself before me; proskyneō = to bow down, prostrate in worship; the word used for worship throughout the NT). The condition is unambiguous and irreducible: to receive what the devil offers requires worshipping the devil. There is no subtlety here, no disguise — the temptation is naked and absolute. The offer encapsulates the entire history of human compromise with evil: gaining the world''s goods, power, or pleasures by paying homage to what opposes God. Jesus refuses not because he does not want the kingdoms but because he will not worship anything other than the Father to obtain them. The cross is the alternative path to all authority (Matthew 28:18: ''All power is given unto me in heaven and in earth'').',
   NULL),
  (8, 'And Jesus answered and said unto him, Get thee behind me, Satan: for it is written, Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God, and him only shalt thou serve.',
   'καὶ ἀποκριθεὶς αὐτῷ εἶπεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς Ὕπαγε Σατανᾶ γέγραπται Κύριον τὸν θεόν σου προσκυνήσεις καὶ αὐτῷ μόνῳ λατρεύσεις',
   'kai apokritheis autō eipen ho Iēsous Hypage Satana gegraptai Kyrion ton theon sou proskynēseis kai autō monō latreuseis',
   '''Get thee behind me, Satan'' (Hypage Satana — go away, Satan; hypage = depart; Luke does not include the ''behind me'' of Matthew 4:10 in many manuscripts, though some do). Jesus''s response is immediate and decisive: no negotiation, no consideration — absolute rejection. ''It is written'' — again Deuteronomy (6:13): ''Thou shalt fear the LORD thy God, and serve him.'' The commandment of exclusive worship is the foundation of the covenant. ''Him only shalt thou serve'' (autō monō latreuseis — him alone you shall worship/serve; latreuō = to render sacred service, to worship; the word for Israel''s whole religious service). The first commandment (Exodus 20:3: ''Thou shalt have no other gods before me'') is upheld. Jesus does not merely refuse Satan; he articulates the positive principle: God alone is to be worshipped.',
   NULL),
  (9, 'And he brought him to Jerusalem, and set him on a pinnacle of the temple, and said unto him, If thou be the Son of God, cast thyself down from hence:',
   'Ἤγαγεν δὲ αὐτὸν εἰς Ἱερουσαλὴμ καὶ ἔστησεν αὐτὸν ἐπὶ τὸ πτερύγιον τοῦ ἱεροῦ καὶ εἶπεν αὐτῷ Εἰ υἱὸς εἶ τοῦ θεοῦ βάλε σεαυτὸν ἐντεῦθεν κάτω',
   'Ēgagen de auton eis Hierousalēm kai estēsen auton epi to pterygion tou hierou kai eipen autō Ei huios ei tou theou bale seauton enteuthen katō',
   '''The pinnacle of the temple'' (pterygion tou hierou — the little wing/pinnacle of the temple; pteryx = wing; possibly the southeastern corner of the temple mount where it towered over the Kidron Valley, a drop of perhaps 450 feet; or the gatehouse at the temple''s highest point). ''If thou be the Son of God'' — the same conditional as the first temptation. The third temptation is the most subtle: Satan now quotes Scripture (Psalm 91:11-12) to support his suggestion. ''Cast thyself down'' — a public miracle that would authenticate Jesus''s divine identity spectacularly before the Jerusalem crowds. The temptation is to use God''s promises as a blank cheque for self-exhibition — to test the Father''s protective faithfulness for personal advantage rather than trusting it in genuine faith.',
   NULL),
  (10, 'For it is written, He shall give his angels charge over thee, to keep thee:',
   'γέγραπται γὰρ ὅτι Τοῖς ἀγγέλοις αὐτοῦ ἐντελεῖται περὶ σοῦ τοῦ διαφυλάξαι σε',
   'gegraptai gar hoti Tois angelois autou entellsetai peri sou tou diaphylaxai se',
   'Satan quotes Psalm 91:11-12 — a psalm of divine protection for the one who trusts in God. The quotation is accurate but the application is perverse: the psalm promises protection for those who trust in God''s providence; Satan invites Jesus to manufacture a crisis to prove the promise. ''He shall give his angels charge over thee'' — the promise of angelic guardianship is real and will be fulfilled in genuine ways (Luke 22:43; Mark 1:13). But the promise cannot be invoked to test God by unnecessary self-endangerment. Satan''s use of Scripture is a warning: the Bible can be quoted to support virtually any human agenda if isolated from its context and purpose. The answer to misused Scripture is not less Scripture but Scripture rightly understood.',
   NULL),
  (11, 'And in their hands they shall bear thee up, lest at any time thou dash thy foot against a stone.',
   'καὶ ὅτι Ἐπὶ χειρῶν ἀροῦσίν σε μήποτε προσκόψῃς πρὸς λίθον τὸν πόδα σου',
   'kai hoti Epi cheirōn arousin se mēpote proskopsēs pros lithon ton poda sou',
   'Satan''s citation of Psalm 91:12 continues. The promise — ''lest thou dash thy foot against a stone'' — was given for the ordinary hazards of the path of obedience, not for voluntarily leaping from heights. The distinction is crucial: God promises to protect his servants in the course of their faithful service; he does not promise miraculous rescue from self-inflicted crises designed to test his reliability. This temptation is directed at presumption — the sin of demanding that God prove himself on our terms. It is essentially a demand for a sign — the same demand that Israel repeatedly made in the wilderness and that Jesus will later refuse (11:29: ''an evil generation seeketh after a sign'').',
   NULL),
  (12, 'And Jesus answering said unto him, It is said, Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God.',
   'καὶ ἀποκριθεὶς εἶπεν αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς ὅτι Εἴρηται Οὐκ ἐκπειράσεις κύριον τὸν θεόν σου',
   'kai apokritheis eipen autō ho Iēsous hoti Eirētai Ouk ekpeiraseis kyrion ton theon sou',
   'Jesus answers with Deuteronomy 6:16: ''Ye shall not tempt the LORD your God, as ye tempted him in Massah.'' The reference is to Exodus 17:1-7 where Israel demanded water and essentially demanded God prove his presence and care (Massah = ''testing''). ''Thou shalt not tempt the Lord thy God'' — to ''tempt'' (ekpeiraseis — from ek-peirazo, an intensified form: to put to the test thoroughly, to try the limits of) God is to presume upon his favour in a way that doubts his genuine faithfulness and demands proof. Jesus refuses to play by Satan''s rules even when Scripture is quoted. He responds not by matching Satan''s citation with a counter-quotation but by identifying the principle that governs all such promises: God is not to be tested.',
   NULL),
  (13, 'And when the devil had ended all the temptation, he departed from him for a season.',
   'Καὶ συντελέσας πάντα πειρασμὸν ὁ διάβολος ἀπέστη ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ ἄχρι καιροῦ',
   'Kai syntelesas panta peirasmon ho diabolos apestē ap autou achri kairou',
   '''When the devil had ended all the temptation'' (syntelesas panta peirasmon — having completed every temptation; syntelesō = to bring to full completion; panta peirasmon = every possible temptation, the full battery). The three explicit temptations are representative; the testing was comprehensive. ''Departed from him for a season'' (apestē ap autou achri kairou — departed from him until an opportune time; kairos = a significant, appointed moment). Luke''s distinctive addition: ''for a season.'' Satan does not give up; he waits for a better opportunity. The ''opportune time'' comes at the Passion (22:3 — ''Satan entered into Judas''; 22:31 — ''Satan hath desired to have you, that he may sift you as wheat''; 22:53 — ''this is your hour, and the power of darkness''). The temptation resumes in Gethsemane and at the cross. Jesus''s victory here is not the final triumph but the decisive victory of the opening battle.',
   NULL),
  (14, 'And Jesus returned in the power of the Spirit into Galilee: and there went out a fame of him through all the region round about.',
   'Καὶ ὑπέστρεψεν ὁ Ἰησοῦς ἐν τῇ δυνάμει τοῦ Πνεύματος εἰς τὴν Γαλιλαίαν καὶ φήμη ἐξῆλθεν καθ᾽ ὅλης τῆς περιχώρου περὶ αὐτοῦ',
   'Kai hypestrepsen ho Iēsous en tē dynamei tou Pneumatos eis tēn Galilaian kai phēmē exēlthen kath holēs tēs perichōrou peri autou',
   '''In the power of the Spirit'' (en tē dynamei tou Pneumatos — in the power of the Spirit; dynamis = power, might, the source of our word ''dynamite''). The same Spirit that filled him (v.1) and led him into the wilderness now fills his Galilean ministry with supernatural power. ''Fame of him'' (phēmē — a report, news; the word for the spreading of news about Jesus; cf. 5:15 where ''so much the more went there a fame abroad''). The public ministry begins with growing popular recognition, which will soon bring both disciples and opposition. Luke summarises the beginning of the Galilean ministry before narrating the paradigmatic episode of the Nazareth rejection, which sets the theological agenda for the whole ministry.',
   NULL),
  (15, 'And he taught in their synagogues, being glorified of all.',
   'καὶ αὐτὸς ἐδίδασκεν ἐν ταῖς συναγωγαῖς αὐτῶν δοξαζόμενος ὑπὸ πάντων',
   'kai autos edidasken en tais synagōgais autōn doxazomenos hypo pantōn',
   '''Taught in their synagogues'' (edidasken en tais synagōgais — was teaching in the synagogues; imperfect, the ongoing practice). The synagogue was the social and religious centre of every Jewish community — a gathering place for prayer, Scripture reading, and teaching on the Sabbath. Any qualified Jewish man could be invited to read and comment on the text. ''Being glorified of all'' (doxazomenos hypo pantōn — being honoured/glorified by all; imperfect, continuous reception of honour). The initial Galilean response is entirely positive — a contrast that makes the Nazareth rejection even more shocking. The synagogue ministry was Jesus''s primary teaching forum throughout the Galilean period.',
   NULL),
  (16, 'And he came to Nazareth, where he had been brought up: and, as his custom was, he went into the synagogue on the sabbath day, and stood up for to read.',
   'Καὶ ἦλθεν εἰς τὴν Ναζαρά οὗ ἦν τεθραμμένος καὶ εἰσῆλθεν κατὰ τὸ εἰωθὸς αὐτῷ ἐν τῇ ἡμέρᾳ τῶν σαββάτων εἰς τὴν συναγωγήν καὶ ἀνέστη ἀναγνῶναι',
   'Kai ēlthen eis tēn Nazara hou ēn tethrammenos kai eisēlthen kata to eiōthos autō en tē hēmera tōn sabbatōn eis tēn synagōgēn kai anestē anagnōnai',
   '''Where he had been brought up'' (hou ēn tethrammenos — where he had been nurtured/raised; trephō = to nourish, bring up). Nazareth was not just his birthplace but his home for approximately 28 years. ''As his custom was'' (kata to eiōthos autō — according to his established habit; eiōthos = what is habitual, customary; the perfect participle indicates a settled, ongoing practice). Jesus''s Sabbath synagogue attendance was not occasional but his regular practice — the custom of a lifetime of covenant faithfulness. ''Stood up for to read'' (anestē anagnōnai — he arose to read; the custom was to stand for the reading of Scripture and sit for the exposition, v.20). The reader was typically invited by the synagogue ruler; Jesus''s standing up may indicate he requested the reading or was invited.',
   NULL),
  (17, 'And there was delivered unto him the book of the prophet Esaias. And when he had opened the book, he found the place where it was written,',
   'καὶ ἐπεδόθη αὐτῷ βιβλίον τοῦ προφήτου Ἠσαΐου καὶ ἀναπτύξας τὸ βιβλίον εὗρεν τὸν τόπον οὗ ἦν γεγραμμένον',
   'kai epedothē autō biblion tou prophētou Hēsaiou kai anaptysas to biblion heuren ton topon hou ēn gegrammenon',
   '''There was delivered unto him the book of the prophet Esaias'' (epedothē autō — was given over to him; the synagogue attendant handed the scroll to Jesus). ''He found the place'' (heuren ton topon — he found the passage; possibly rolled to a specific section; the scroll of Isaiah is long, and finding a specific passage required skill and intention). The passage read (Isaiah 61:1-2) was divinely chosen, whether by providential assignment in the lectionary cycle or by Jesus''s deliberate selection. It is the most programmatic Messianic text possible: the Servant anointed with the Spirit, commissioned to preach good news to the poor. Jesus does not choose a general text but the specific passage that defines his entire mission. The selection itself is an act of self-identification.',
   NULL),
  (18, 'The Spirit of the Lord is upon me, because he hath anointed me to preach the gospel to the poor; he hath sent me to heal the brokenhearted, to preach deliverance to the captives, and recovering of sight to the blind, to set at liberty them that are bruised,',
   'Πνεῦμα κυρίου ἐπ᾽ ἐμέ οὗ εἵνεκεν ἔχρισέν με εὐαγγελίσασθαι πτωχοῖς ἀπέσταλκέν με κηρύξαι αἰχμαλώτοις ἄφεσιν καὶ τυφλοῖς ἀνάβλεψιν ἀποστεῖλαι τεθραυσμένους ἐν ἀφέσει',
   'Pneuma kyriou ep eme hou heineken echrisen me euangelisasthai ptōchois apestalken me kēryxai aichmalōtois aphesin kai typhlois anablepsin aposteilai tethrausmenous en aphesei',
   'Isaiah 61:1-2 — the programmatic text of Jesus''s mission. ''The Spirit of the Lord is upon me'' — Jesus''s ministry is Trinitarian: he is anointed (by the Father) with the Spirit at the baptism (3:22). ''Because he hath anointed me'' (echrisen me — he anointed me; the verb from which ''Christ'' = Anointed One derives). Jesus declares himself to be the Anointed Servant of Isaiah 61. ''Preach the gospel to the poor'' (euangelisasthai ptōchois — to announce good news to the destitute; ptōchos = the completely destitute, not just financially poor but spiritually and socially marginalised). ''Deliverance to the captives'' (aichmalōtois aphesin — release to prisoners of war). ''Recovering of sight to the blind'' (typhlois anablepsin — seeing again to the blind; the miracles of healing will fulfil this literally). ''Set at liberty them that are bruised'' (tethrausmenous en aphesei — the crushed, battered ones in release/freedom). The Jubilee language: the year of release, the year of the LORD''s favour.',
   NULL),
  (19, 'To preach the acceptable year of the Lord.',
   'κηρύξαι ἐνιαυτὸν κυρίου δεκτόν',
   'kēryxai eniauton kyriou dekton',
   '''The acceptable year of the Lord'' (eniauton kyriou dekton — the year of the Lord''s favour/acceptance). Jesus stops reading in the middle of Isaiah 61:2 (the full verse continues ''and the day of vengeance of our God'' — which he deliberately omits). The Jubilee (Leviticus 25) was the fiftieth year when debts were cancelled, slaves were freed, and land returned to original owners. Jesus announces the ultimate Jubilee — the year of God''s grace and favour in which the spiritual realities symbolised by the Jubilee are actualised. The Jubilee language is all about release: from debt, slavery, poverty, and alienation. Jesus is the fulfilment of the Jubilee principle — his death cancels the debt of sin; his resurrection releases prisoners; his gospel restores the alienated to their inheritance.',
   NULL),
  (20, 'And he closed the book, and he gave it again to the minister, and sat down. And the eyes of all them that were in the synagogue were fastened on him.',
   'καὶ πτύξας τὸ βιβλίον ἀποδοὺς τῷ ὑπηρέτῃ ἐκάθισεν καὶ πάντων οἱ ὀφθαλμοὶ ἐν τῇ συναγωγῇ ἦσαν ἀτενίζοντες αὐτῷ',
   'kai ptyxas to biblion apodous tō hypēretē ekathisen kai pantōn hoi ophthalmoi en tē synagōgē ēsan atenizaontes autō',
   '''He closed the book'' — the deliberate act of rolling up the scroll and handing it back. ''Sat down'' (ekathisen — he sat down; the teacher''s posture for exposition in the rabbinic tradition). ''The eyes of all them...were fastened on him'' (panton hoi ophthalmoi ēsan atenizaontes — all eyes were fixed on him; atenizō = to fix the gaze intently, to stare; a Lukan word, cf. Acts 3:4; 6:15; 7:55; 10:4). The congregation is riveted in expectation. They have heard the reading; now they wait for the interpretation. The moment of tension between reading and exposition is extended by Luke to dramatic effect — every eye on the one who is about to make the most extraordinary claim in the history of the synagogue.',
   NULL),
  (21, 'And he began to say unto them, This day is this scripture fulfilled in your ears.',
   'ἤρξατο δὲ λέγειν πρὸς αὐτοὺς ὅτι Σήμερον πεπλήρωται ἡ γραφὴ αὕτη ἐν τοῖς ὠσὶν ὑμῶν',
   'ērxato de legein pros autous hoti Sēmeron peplērōtai hē graphē hautē en tois ōsin hymōn',
   '''This day is this scripture fulfilled in your ears'' (Sēmeron peplērōtai hē graphē hautē — today this scripture has been fulfilled; sēmeron = today, this very day; peplērōtai = perfect passive, has been and remains fulfilled). This is the most audacious synagogue sermon in history. Jesus does not say ''this scripture will be fulfilled when the Messiah comes'' — he says it is fulfilled today, in your hearing, by me. The claim is simultaneously exegetical (the text refers to the Messiah), historical (the Messiah has now come), and personal (I am he). ''In your ears'' (en tois ōsin hymōn — in your ears; not just ''to you'' but ''as you are hearing it''). The fulfilment is happening in real time, in the act of his reading and speaking. This single sentence is the christological hinge of the entire Lukan narrative.',
   NULL),
  (22, 'And all bare him witness, and wondered at the gracious words which proceeded out of his mouth. And they said, Is not this Joseph''s son?',
   'καὶ πάντες ἐμαρτύρουν αὐτῷ καὶ ἐθαύμαζον ἐπὶ τοῖς λόγοις τῆς χάριτος τοῖς ἐκπορευομένοις ἐκ τοῦ στόματος αὐτοῦ καὶ ἔλεγον Οὐχὶ υἱός ἐστιν Ἰωσὴφ οὗτος',
   'kai pantes emartyroun autō kai ethaumazon epi tois logois tēs charitos tois ekporeuomenois ek tou stomatos autou kai elegon Ouchi huios estin Iōsēph houtos',
   '''All bare him witness'' (pantes emartyroun autō — all were testifying to him, speaking well of him; imperfect: a sustained initial reaction of positive response). ''The gracious words'' (tois logois tēs charitos — the words of grace; logos tēs charitos = speech characterised by grace/favour; not just pleasant words but words full of divine grace). The congregation initially receives the teaching positively — they are drawn in by the beauty and authority of his speech. ''Is not this Joseph''s son?'' (Ouchi huios estin Iōsēph houtos — Is this not the son of Joseph?) — the question reveals the barrier that prevents full acceptance: they know his human family. The familiarity of thirty years of village life becomes the obstacle to recognising his divine identity. What should be an asset — knowing his home, his family — becomes the stumbling block.',
   NULL),
  (23, 'And he said unto them, Ye will surely say unto me this proverb, Physician, heal thyself: whatsoever we have heard done in Capernaum, do also here in thy country.',
   'καὶ εἶπεν πρὸς αὐτούς Πάντως ἐρεῖτέ μοι τὴν παραβολὴν ταύτην Ἰατρέ θεράπευσον σεαυτόν ὅσα ἠκούσαμεν γενόμενα εἰς τὴν Καφαρναοὺμ ποίησον καὶ ὧδε ἐν τῇ πατρίδι σου',
   'kai eipen pros autous Pantōs ereite moi tēn parabolēn tautēn Iatre therapeuson seauton hosa ēkousamen genomena eis tēn Kapharnaoum poieson kai hōde en tē patridi sou',
   '''Physician, heal thyself'' (Iatre therapeuson seauton — Doctor, heal yourself; a common proverb in the ancient world). Jesus reads the subtext of their wonder: they want signs and miracles for their own benefit, as they have heard he performed in Capernaum. ''Do also here in thy country'' — the demand for local miracles to authenticate his claim. The proverb implies: if you are truly capable, demonstrate it here where we can see and assess it. Jesus perceives the unbelief beneath the initial positive response. The demand for local miracles reflects the same spirit as the temptation to cast himself from the pinnacle: use your power to prove yourself on the terms others demand. Jesus refuses this consistently — miracles come in response to faith, not as a means of producing it on demand (cf. 11:29).',
   NULL),
  (24, 'And he said, Verily I say unto you, No prophet is accepted in his own country.',
   'εἶπεν δέ Ἀμὴν λέγω ὑμῖν ὅτι οὐδεὶς προφήτης δεκτός ἐστιν ἐν τῇ πατρίδι αὐτοῦ',
   'eipen de Amēn legō hymin hoti oudeis prophētēs dektos estin en tē patridi autou',
   '''Verily I say unto you'' (Amēn legō hymin — truly/amen I say to you). ''Amēn'' as an introductory formula is unique to Jesus among all ancient Jewish teachers — rabbis said ''Amēn'' to endorse what others had said, at the end of prayers; Jesus uses it to introduce his own authoritative teaching. ''No prophet is accepted in his own country'' (oudeis prophētēs dektos estin en tē patridi autou — no prophet is acceptable/welcome in his homeland). The proverb, applied to himself, is a warning: the Nazareth congregation''s familiarity with him will prevent them from receiving him as a prophet. Familiarity breeds contempt — or at least comfortable assumption. Those who knew Jesus as a boy cannot easily accept him as the Messiah. The same principle operates today: those closest to Jesus in social proximity are not necessarily those closest to him in faith.',
   NULL),
  (25, 'But I tell you of a truth, many widows were in Israel in the days of Elias, when the heaven was shut up three years and six months, when great famine was throughout all the land;',
   'ἐπ᾽ ἀληθείας δὲ λέγω ὑμῖν πολλαὶ χῆραι ἦσαν ἐν ταῖς ἡμέραις Ἠλίου ἐν τῷ Ἰσραήλ ὅτε ἐκλείσθη ὁ οὐρανὸς ἐπὶ ἔτη τρία καὶ μῆνας ἕξ ὡς ἐγένετο λιμὸς μέγας ἐπὶ πᾶσαν τὴν γῆν',
   'ep alētheias de legō hymin pollai chērai ēsan en tais hēmerais Hēliou en tō Israēl hote ekleisthē ho ouranos epi etē tria kai mēnas hex hōs egeneto limos megas epi pasan tēn gēn',
   '''Many widows were in Israel in the days of Elias'' — the first of two OT precedents Jesus cites (Elijah and Elisha) to demonstrate that God''s grace has historically broken the ethnic/national boundaries of Israel to reach Gentiles. The three-and-a-half year drought (1 Kings 17-18; James 5:17: ''it rained not on the earth by the space of three years and six months'') caused widespread famine throughout Israel. ''Many widows'' in Israel suffered — yet God did not send Elijah to any of them. The implication for the Nazareth congregation is painfully sharp: God is not obligated to bless Israel''s hometown (or Israel itself) simply because of national privilege. He sends grace where it is received.',
   NULL),
  (26, 'But unto none of them was Elias sent, save unto Sarepta, a city of Sidon, unto a woman that was a widow.',
   'καὶ πρὸς οὐδεμίαν αὐτῶν ἐπέμφθη Ἠλίας εἰ μὴ εἰς Σάρεπτα τῆς Σιδωνίας πρὸς γυναῖκα χήραν',
   'kai pros oudemian autōn epemphthē Hēlias ei mē eis Sarepta tēs Sidōnias pros gynaika chēran',
   '''Sarepta...Sidon'' — a Gentile city in Phoenicia (modern Lebanon), far north of Israel (1 Kings 17:8-24). The widow of Zarephath (Sarepta) was not a Jew but a Phoenician — a Gentile woman who received the blessing of Elijah''s presence and miracle (the inexhaustible meal and oil, the resurrection of her son). God''s sovereign grace bypassed the many widows of Israel to reach one Gentile widow. The pattern anticipates the whole Gentile mission of Luke-Acts: when Israel rejects the gospel, it goes to the Gentiles (Acts 13:46; 18:6; 28:28). Jesus is not simply making an historical observation; he is warning the Nazareth congregation that their rejection of him will result in the grace flowing to others.',
   NULL),
  (27, 'And many lepers were in Israel in the time of Eliseus the prophet; and none of them was cleansed, saving Naaman the Syrian.',
   'καὶ πολλοὶ λεπροὶ ἦσαν ἐν τῷ Ἰσραὴλ ἐπὶ Ἐλισαίου τοῦ προφήτου καὶ οὐδεὶς αὐτῶν ἐκαθαρίσθη εἰ μὴ Ναιμὰν ὁ Σύρος',
   'kai polloi leproi ēsan en tō Israēl epi Elisaiou tou prophētou kai oudeis autōn ekatharisthē ei mē Naiman ho Syros',
   '''Naaman the Syrian'' (Naiman ho Syros — Naaman the Syrian; 2 Kings 5). Naaman was the commander of Syria''s army — an enemy of Israel — who was cleansed of leprosy by Elisha. Many lepers in Israel went uncleansed; the one Gentile enemy commander received healing. The pattern is the same: God''s grace bypassing the national Israel to reach an individual Gentile who came in humility and faith. Naaman''s story has the additional element of resistance — he almost refused to obey Elisha''s undignified instruction to wash in the Jordan seven times (2 Kings 5:11-13). The double example of the widow of Zarephath (woman) and Naaman (man) is comprehensive: both sexes, Phoenicia and Syria, north and east — the grace of God knows no national boundaries.',
   NULL),
  (28, 'And all they in the synagogue, when they heard these things, were filled with wrath,',
   'καὶ ἐπλήσθησαν πάντες θυμοῦ ἐν τῇ συναγωγῇ ἀκούοντες ταῦτα',
   'kai eplēsthēsan pantes thymou en tē synagōgē akouontes tauta',
   '''Were filled with wrath'' (eplēsthēsan pantes thymou — all were filled with rage; plēroō = to fill; thymos = passionate anger, rage; the strongest Greek word for anger). The shift from v.22 (''all bare him witness and wondered'') to v.28 (''filled with wrath'') is dramatic and instantaneous. What changed? Jesus''s implication that God''s grace was going to Gentiles while bypassing unbelieving Israel. The congregation could accept that he was a gifted teacher; they could not accept that their national privilege was not automatic, that their rejection of him would result in the blessing flowing to others. Ethnic-religious pride is the most tenacious human sin, and Jesus has directly attacked it. The same message produces wonder when it offers grace and rage when it removes privilege.',
   NULL),
  (29, 'And rose up, and thrust him out of the city, and led him unto the brow of the hill whereon their city was built, that they might cast him down headlong.',
   'καὶ ἀναστάντες ἐξέβαλον αὐτὸν ἔξω τῆς πόλεως καὶ ἤγαγον αὐτὸν ἕως ὀφρύος τοῦ ὄρους ἐφ᾽ οὗ ἡ πόλις ᾠκοδόμητο αὐτῶν εἰς τὸ κατακρημνίσαι αὐτόν',
   'kai anastantes exebalon auton exō tēs poleōs kai ēgagon auton heōs ophryos tou orous eph hou hē polis ōkodomēto autōn eis to katakrēmnisai auton',
   '''Rose up, and thrust him out'' (exebalon auton — they threw him out; ekballō = to cast out; the forceful, violent ejection). The synagogue congregation becomes a mob. ''Led him unto the brow of the hill'' (eos ophryos tou orous — to the edge/brow of the mountain; ophrys = eyebrow, edge, brow). Nazareth sits on the edge of a hill with rocky escarpments. ''Cast him down headlong'' (katakrēmnisai — to throw down a precipice; katakrēmnizomai = to cast down a cliff). This was both mob violence and possibly an attempt at extra-legal execution: throwing from a height was a form of death sentence sometimes applied outside formal legal processes. The Passion narrative begins in Nazareth: the first attempt on Jesus''s life comes from his own hometown.',
   NULL),
  (30, 'But he passing through the midst of them went his way.',
   'αὐτὸς δὲ διελθὼν διὰ μέσου αὐτῶν ἐπορεύετο',
   'autos de dielthōn dia mesou autōn eporeueto',
   '''Passing through the midst of them went his way'' (dielthōn dia mesou autōn eporeueto — passing through the middle of them, he was going on his way). No explanation is given of how Jesus escaped — the text simply records that he passed through them. This has been interpreted as: a miraculous invisibility, a divine restraint on the mob, or simply a calm authority that checked their violence. Luke''s understated narration is deliberate: it is not the moment for Jesus to die (cf. John 7:30; 8:20: ''his hour was not yet come''). The time and manner of his death are under divine control. He goes on his way — the way of the cross, on God''s timetable, not in Nazareth at the hands of an angry synagogue congregation.',
   NULL),
  (31, 'And came down to Capernaum, a city of Galilee, and taught them on the sabbath days.',
   'Καὶ κατῆλθεν εἰς Καφαρναοὺμ πόλιν τῆς Γαλιλαίας καὶ ἦν διδάσκων αὐτοὺς ἐν τοῖς σάββασιν',
   'Kai katēlthen eis Kapharnaoum polin tēs Galilaias kai ēn didaskōn autous en tois sabbasin',
   '''Came down to Capernaum'' (katēlthen eis Kapharnaoum — he went down to Capernaum; Nazareth is at a higher elevation than Capernaum on the shore of the Sea of Galilee). Capernaum became Jesus''s operational headquarters for the Galilean ministry (Matthew 4:13: ''he...dwelt in Capernaum''). The shift from rejected Nazareth to receptive Capernaum illustrates the Elijah/Elisha principle just enunciated: grace goes where it is received. Capernaum is a fishing village on the northern shore of the Sea of Galilee; its synagogue (discovered archaeologically) was probably built near the time of Jesus or earlier. ''Was teaching on the sabbath days'' (ēn didaskōn en tois sabbasin — was teaching on the sabbaths; imperfect: ongoing, habitual practice).',
   NULL),
  (32, 'And they were astonished at his doctrine: for his word was with power.',
   'καὶ ἐξεπλήσσοντο ἐπὶ τῇ διδαχῇ αὐτοῦ ὅτι ἐν ἐξουσίᾳ ἦν ὁ λόγος αὐτοῦ',
   'kai exeplēssonto epi tē didachē autou hoti en exousia ēn ho logos autou',
   '''Astonished at his doctrine'' (exeplēssonto epi tē didachē autou — they were struck with astonishment at his teaching; exeplēssō = to strike out; the same root as ekplēssō in 2:47 for the temple teachers'' astonishment at the twelve-year-old Jesus). ''His word was with power'' (en exousia ēn ho logos autou — his word was with authority; exousia = authority, the right and power to act; distinct from dynamis [miraculous power] though related). The Capernaum congregation senses immediately what makes Jesus different from the scribes: he speaks with direct divine authority, not by citing other authorities (''Rabbi X says...''). His word has inherent authority because it is the word of God himself speaking through his Son.',
   NULL),
  (33, 'And in the synagogue there was a man, which had a spirit of an unclean devil, and cried out with a loud voice,',
   'καὶ ἐν τῇ συναγωγῇ ἦν ἄνθρωπος ἔχων πνεῦμα δαιμονίου ἀκαθάρτου καὶ ἀνέκραξεν φωνῇ μεγάλῃ',
   'kai en tē synagōgē ēn anthrōpos echōn pneuma daimoniou akathartou kai anekraxen phōnē megalē',
   '''A spirit of an unclean devil'' (pneuma daimoniou akathartou — a spirit of an unclean demon; daimonion = demon, unclean spirit; akathartou = unclean, morally impure). The demon''s manifestation in a synagogue — the place of worship and Torah study — is significant: the presence of Jesus triggers demonic reaction. The demons recognise Jesus immediately (v.34) even when humans do not. ''Cried out with a loud voice'' (anekraxen phōnē megalē — shouted with a great voice) — the demon''s agitation at the presence of the Holy One is visible and audible. The synagogue in Capernaum was Jesus''s first major public confrontation with demonic power, establishing the pattern of the coming kingdom: where Jesus goes, demons must flee.',
   NULL),
  (34, 'Saying, Let us alone; what have we to do with thee, thou Jesus of Nazareth? art thou come to destroy us? I know thee who thou art; the Holy One of God.',
   'Ἔα τί ἡμῖν καὶ σοί Ἰησοῦ Ναζαρηνέ ἦλθες ἀπολέσαι ἡμᾶς οἶδά σε τίς εἶ ὁ Ἅγιος τοῦ θεοῦ',
   'Ea ti hēmin kai soi Iēsou Nazarēne ēlthes apolesai hēmas oida se tis ei ho Hagios tou theou',
   '''Let us alone'' (Ea — an exclamation of protest: leave off! stop!; a word of alarm and resistance). ''What have we to do with thee?'' (ti hēmin kai soi — what is there between us and you?; a Semitic idiom expressing total separation of interests). ''Art thou come to destroy us?'' — the demon correctly perceives that the coming of the Holy One means its destruction. ''I know thee who thou art'' (oida se tis ei — I know you who you are; oida = to know with certainty). ''The Holy One of God'' (ho Hagios tou theou — the Holy One of God; the most exalted title; used in the OT for the LORD himself in Psalm 71:22; Isaiah 1:4; 30:11 as ''the Holy One of Israel''). The demonic confession is the most accurate christological statement in Capernaum''s synagogue that day — yet Jesus refuses to accept it. Correct doctrine from the wrong source, in the wrong context, for the wrong purpose is not welcome.',
   NULL),
  (35, 'And Jesus rebuked him, saying, Hold thy peace, and come out of him. And when the devil had thrown him in the midst, he came out of him, and hurt him not.',
   'καὶ ἐπετίμησεν αὐτῷ ὁ Ἰησοῦς λέγων Φιμώθητι καὶ ἔξελθε ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ καὶ ῥίψαν αὐτὸν τὸ δαιμόνιον εἰς μέσον ἐξῆλθεν ἀπ᾽ αὐτοῦ μηδὲν βλάψαν αὐτόν',
   'kai epetimēsen autō ho Iēsous legōn Phimōthēti kai exelthe ap autou kai rhipsan auton to daimonion eis meson exēlthen ap autou mēden blabpsan auton',
   '''Rebuked'' (epetimēsen — he rebuked/commanded with authority; epitimaō = to rebuke, censure, charge with authority). ''Hold thy peace'' (Phimōthēti — be muzzled, be silenced; phimoō = to muzzle; used of silencing oxen in 1 Corinthians 9:9 and of Jesus silencing the storm in Mark 4:39). The two commands are absolute: Silence! Out! Both are obeyed instantly. ''He came out of him, and hurt him not'' (exēlthen...mēden blabsan auton — came out...having harmed him nothing). The demon obeys — throwing the man down in its departure (a final act of spite or involuntary convulsion) — but cannot harm him. Jesus''s authority over demonic power is total: the demon must leave, must be silent, and cannot cause lasting harm. The man is left whole.',
   NULL),
  (36, 'And they were all amazed, and spake among themselves, saying, What a word is this! for with authority and power he commandeth the unclean spirits, and they come out.',
   'καὶ ἐγένετο θάμβος ἐπὶ πάντας καὶ συνελάλουν πρὸς ἀλλήλους λέγοντες Τίς ὁ λόγος οὗτος ὅτι ἐν ἐξουσίᾳ καὶ δυνάμει ἐπιτάσσει τοῖς ἀκαθάρτοις πνεύμασιν καὶ ἐξέρχονται',
   'kai egeneto thambos epi pantas kai synelaloun pros allēlous legontes Tis ho logos houtos hoti en exousia kai dynamei epitassei tois akathartois pneumasin kai exerchontai',
   '''Amazement'' (thambos — astonishment, wonder, reverential awe; a stronger word than thaumazō). ''What a word is this!'' (Tis ho logos houtos — what is this word?). The congregation focuses on the word — Jesus commands with a word and the demon obeys. ''With authority and power'' (en exousia kai dynamei — in authority and power; exousia = the right/authority to command; dynamis = the power/ability to execute). Both together: the right to command and the ability to compel. Jesus has both; the scribes and Pharisees have neither over demons. ''They come out'' (exerchontai — present tense: they keep coming out; the generalisation from this one case to the ongoing pattern). The exorcism authenticates his teaching: the word that commands demons is the word that teaches with authority — both are from the same source.',
   NULL),
  (37, 'And the fame of him went out into every place of the country round about.',
   'καὶ ἐξεπορεύετο ἦχος περὶ αὐτοῦ εἰς πάντα τόπον τῆς περιχώρου',
   'kai exeporeueto ēchos peri autou eis panta topon tēs perichōrou',
   '''The fame of him went out'' (exeporeueto ēchos peri autou — there went out a sound/report about him; ēchos = a sound, noise, echo; our word ''echo'' comes from this Greek word). The news of what happened in the synagogue spread organically throughout the surrounding region. Luke''s verb ēchos (echo, sound) is vivid: the news resonated and reverberated like sound waves through the area. This growing fame will bring the crowds that fill the next scenes (vv.40-41). The public ministry of Jesus generates its own momentum: healings and exorcisms produce reports that draw more people seeking healing, which creates opportunities for more teaching and more healing. The kingdom advances both through direct ministry and through the reports it generates.',
   NULL),
  (38, 'And he arose out of the synagogue, and entered into Simon''s house. And Simon''s wife''s mother was taken with a great fever; and they besought him for her.',
   'Ἀναστὰς δὲ ἀπὸ τῆς συναγωγῆς εἰσῆλθεν εἰς τὴν οἰκίαν Σίμωνος πενθερὰ δὲ τοῦ Σίμωνος ἦν συνεχομένη πυρετῷ μεγάλῳ καὶ ἠρώτησαν αὐτὸν περὶ αὐτῆς',
   'Anastas de apo tēs synagōgēs eisēlthen eis tēn oikian Simōnos penthera de tou Simōnos ēn synechomenē pyretō megalō kai ērōtēsan auton peri autēs',
   '''Simon''s house'' — Peter (Simon) was from Bethsaida (John 1:44) but had a house in Capernaum — his wife''s family home, perhaps. Peter is already known to Jesus (he will be formally called in Luke 5:1-11), and the house becomes a base of operations. ''A great fever'' (pyretō megalō — a great/high fever; Luke alone specifies ''great,'' showing his physician''s interest in degree of illness). ''They besought him for her'' (ērōtēsan auton peri autēs — they asked him concerning her; the family intercedes for the sick woman). This is a pattern in the Gospels: others ask on behalf of the sick or demon-possessed. Intercession for others is honoured by Jesus consistently (cf. 7:2-3; 8:41-42; Matthew 15:22-28; John 11:3).',
   NULL),
  (39, 'And he stood over her, and rebuked the fever; and it left her: and immediately she arose and ministered unto them.',
   'καὶ ἐπιστὰς ἐπάνω αὐτῆς ἐπετίμησεν τῷ πυρετῷ καὶ ἀφῆκεν αὐτήν παραχρῆμα δὲ ἀναστᾶσα διηκόνει αὐτοῖς',
   'kai epistas epanō autēs epetimēsen tō pyretō kai aphēken autēn parachrēma de anastasa diēkonei autois',
   '''Stood over her, and rebuked the fever'' (epetimēsen tō pyretō — he rebuked the fever). Luke uniquely uses the same verb ''rebuked'' (epitimaō) for the fever that was used for the demon in v.35. Whether the fever was itself demonic or simply a natural disease treated with the same sovereign authority is unclear; Luke''s use of the same vocabulary suggests Jesus exercises the same royal authority over physical illness that he exercises over demonic possession. ''Immediately she arose and ministered'' (parachrēma de anastasa diēkonei autois — at once, having arisen, she was serving them; diakoneo = to serve at table, to minister). The completeness of the healing: not just fever gone but full strength immediately restored. Her response to healing is service — the pattern of genuine discipleship.',
   NULL),
  (40, 'Now when the sun was setting, all they that had any sick with divers diseases brought them unto him; and he laid his hands on every one of them, and healed them.',
   'Δύνοντος δὲ τοῦ ἡλίου ἅπαντες ὅσοι εἶχον ἀσθενοῦντας νόσοις ποικίλαις ἤγαγον αὐτοὺς πρὸς αὐτόν ὁ δὲ ἑνὶ ἑκάστῳ αὐτῶν τὰς χεῖρας ἐπιτιθεὶς ἐθεράπευεν αὐτούς',
   'Dynontos de tou hēliou hapantes hosoi eichon asthenountas nosois poikilais ēgagon autous pros auton ho de heni hekastō autōn tas cheiras epititheis etherapeuen autous',
   '''When the sun was setting'' (Dynontos tou hēliou — at the setting of the sun; the Sabbath ended at sunset, at which point it was permissible to carry the sick without violating Sabbath restrictions on work and burden-carrying). The community brings their sick to Jesus the moment the Sabbath legally ends — they have waited all day, watching Jesus''s synagogue ministry from a distance. ''All they that had any sick'' (hapantes hosoi eichon asthenountas — all those who had sick people). The universal scope of the healing ministry: every sick person in Capernaum is brought. ''He laid his hands on every one of them'' (heni hekastō autōn tas cheiras epititheis — placing his hands on each one of them individually). Not a mass-healing word but individual, personal touch for each — the pastoral care of the infinite for the individual. ''And healed them'' — the comprehensive result.',
   NULL),
  (41, 'And devils also came out of many, crying out, and saying, Thou art Christ the Son of God. And he rebuking them suffered them not to speak: for they knew that he was Christ.',
   'ἐξήρχετο δὲ καὶ δαιμόνια ἀπὸ πολλῶν κράζοντα καὶ λέγοντα ὅτι Σὺ εἶ ὁ υἱὸς τοῦ θεοῦ καὶ ἐπιτιμῶν οὐκ εἴα αὐτὰ λαλεῖν ὅτι ᾔδεισαν τὸν Χριστὸν αὐτὸν εἶναι',
   'exērcheto de kai daimonia apo pollōn krazonta kai legonta hoti Sy ei ho huios tou theou kai epitimōn ouk eia auta lalein hoti ēdeisan ton Christon auton einai',
   '''Thou art Christ the Son of God'' — the demons'' confession at Capernaum is even more explicit than in the synagogue: ''the Son of God.'' ''He rebuking them suffered them not to speak'' (epitimōn ouk eia auta lalein — rebuking, he was not permitting them to speak; the messianic secret). Why does Jesus silence the demons? Multiple reasons: (1) demonic testimony, however accurate, is tainted — they serve the wrong master; (2) the correct understanding of ''Christ'' and ''Son of God'' requires the cross and resurrection — premature Messianic proclamation would create wrong expectations; (3) Jesus''s identity is to be revealed through his works and ultimately through his death and resurrection, not through demonic proclamation. ''For they knew that he was Christ'' (oti ēdeisan ton Christon auton einai — because they knew him to be the Christ/Messiah). The irony: the demons know what most humans do not yet see.',
   NULL),
  (42, 'And when it was day, he departed and went into a desert place: and the people sought him, and came unto him, and stayed him, that he should not depart from them.',
   'Γενομένης δὲ ἡμέρας ἐξελθὼν ἐπορεύθη εἰς ἔρημον τόπον καὶ οἱ ὄχλοι ἐπεζήτουν αὐτόν καὶ ἦλθον ἕως αὐτοῦ καὶ κατεῖχον αὐτὸν τοῦ μὴ πορεύεσθαι ἀπ᾽ αὐτῶν',
   'Genomenēs de hēmeras exelthōn eporeuthē eis erēmon topon kai hoi ochloi epezētoun auton kai ēlthan heōs autou kai kateichon auton tou mē poreuesthai ap autōn',
   '''A desert place'' (erēmon topon — a solitary, deserted place) — Jesus''s withdrawal for prayer and solitude (cf. 5:16; Mark 1:35: ''in the morning, rising up a great while before day, he went out, and departed into a solitary place, and there prayed''). Prayer marks every decisive moment of Jesus''s life in Luke. After a night of healing and exorcism, the morning is for prayer. ''The people sought him'' (epezētoun auton — were seeking him; imperfect: persistent seeking). ''Stayed him, that he should not depart from them'' (kateichon auton tou mē poreuesthai — they were holding him back from going away; katechō = to hold down, restrain; the people want to keep Jesus as their local healer and teacher). Jesus resists this local ownership of his ministry — his mission is not to one place but to the world.',
   NULL),
  (43, 'And he said unto them, I must preach the kingdom of God to other cities also: for therefore am I sent.',
   'ὁ δὲ εἶπεν πρὸς αὐτούς ὅτι καὶ ταῖς ἑτέραις πόλεσιν εὐαγγελίσασθαί με δεῖ τὴν βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ ὅτι ἐπὶ τοῦτο ἀπεστάλην',
   'ho de eipen pros autous hoti kai tais heterais polesin euangelisasthai me dei tēn basileian tou theou hoti epi touto apestalēn',
   '''I must'' (dei — it is divinely necessary; the word of divine compulsion). ''Preach the kingdom of God to other cities also'' (tais heterais polesin euangelisasthai — to proclaim the good news of the kingdom of God to the other cities also). Jesus''s mission is not local but universal. ''For therefore am I sent'' (oti epi touto apestalēn — because for this purpose I have been sent; apostellō = to send with authority and commission; the same verb as ''apostle''). Jesus defines himself in terms of his commission: he is the Sent One, the Apostle of the Father (Hebrews 3:1). His purpose is determined not by popular demand (Capernaum wants him to stay) but by divine commission. The ''kingdom of God'' (basileia tou theou) — the central theme of Jesus''s preaching in Luke — is the dynamic reign of God breaking in through Jesus''s words and deeds.',
   NULL),
  (44, 'And he preached in the synagogues of Galilee.',
   'καὶ ἦν κηρύσσων εἰς τὰς συναγωγὰς τῆς Γαλιλαίας',
   'kai ēn kēryssōn eis tas synagōgas tēs Galilaias',
   '''He preached in the synagogues of Galilee'' (ēn kēryssōn — was proclaiming; imperfect: ongoing, habitual). Luke''s summary statement closes the chapter and anticipates the extended Galilean ministry that follows. Some manuscripts read ''Judea'' instead of ''Galilee'' — if so, it refers to the broader Jewish territory (Judea in its widest sense including Galilee). The synagogue network provided Jesus with a ready-made communication infrastructure: every Jewish village had one, operating on a regular weekly schedule, with an established practice of inviting visiting teachers to speak. Jesus uses this network systematically to proclaim the kingdom throughout Galilee. The circuit preaching of the itinerant prophet-teacher is the model for the apostolic mission that follows in Acts.',
   NULL)
) AS v(verse_number, kjv_text, original_text, transliteration, study_note, doctrinal_note)
WHERE b.name = 'Luke' AND c.chapter_number = 4;
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- LUKE CHAPTER 4 — BACKFILL: Word Studies + Cross References
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════

INSERT INTO word_studies (verse_id, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
SELECT v.id, w.original_word, w.transliteration, w.strongs_number, w.meaning, w.word_order
FROM verses v JOIN chapters c ON v.chapter_id = c.id JOIN books b ON c.book_id = b.id
CROSS JOIN (VALUES
  (1, 'πλήρης πνεύματος ἁγίου', 'plērēs pneumatos hagiou', 'G4134/G4151/G40', 'Full of the Holy Ghost — Jesus enters the wilderness in fullness of the Spirit, contrasting Adam''s fall in plenty. The Spirit himself "led" him into testing.', 1),
  (1, 'ἤγετο ἐν τῷ πνεύματι', 'ēgeto en tō pneumati', 'G71/G4151', 'Was led by the Spirit — imperfect passive, continuous Spirit-led movement. The temptation is divinely orchestrated, not Satanic ambush.', 2),
  (2, 'ἡμέρας τεσσαράκοντα', 'hēmeras tessarakonta', 'G2250/G5062', 'Forty days — recapitulates Israel''s 40 years and Moses''s 40 days on Sinai (Ex 34:28). Jesus succeeds where Israel failed.', 3),
  (2, 'πειραζόμενος ὑπὸ τοῦ διαβόλου', 'peirazomenos hypo tou diabolou', 'G3985/G1228', 'Tempted by the devil — diabolos = "slanderer, accuser." All three temptations target the Father-Son relationship just declared at the baptism.', 4),
  (4, 'γέγραπται', 'gegraptai', 'G1125', 'It is written — perfect passive of graphō, "it stands written" with abiding force. Jesus answers each temptation by appeal to Deuteronomy.', 5),
  (8, 'προσκυνήσεις', 'proskynēseis', 'G4352', 'Thou shalt worship — prostration in submission. Reserved for God alone (Deut 6:13); Satan''s offer would constitute idolatry.', 6),
  (10, 'ἐντελεῖται', 'enteleitai', 'G1781', 'Shall give charge — Satan misquotes Ps 91:11-12 to tempt Jesus to presume on God''s protection. Scripture twisted is still Satanic in mouth.', 7),
  (12, 'ἐκπειράσεις', 'ekpeiraseis', 'G1598', 'Shalt thou tempt — intensified peirazō, to put to the test. Quoted from Deut 6:16, referring to Israel at Massah.', 8),
  (13, 'ἄχρι καιροῦ', 'achri kairou', 'G891/G2540', 'Until a season — the devil departs only temporarily. He returns through Judas and the Cross (22:3, 53). The conflict is unresolved until Calvary.', 9),
  (14, 'ἐν τῇ δυνάμει τοῦ πνεύματος', 'en tē dynamei tou pneumatos', 'G1411/G4151', 'In the power of the Spirit — Jesus emerges from temptation not weakened but invested with proven Spirit-empowered authority.', 10),
  (16, 'κατὰ τὸ εἰωθὸς αὐτῷ', 'kata to eiōthos autō', 'G1486', 'According to his custom — Jesus habitually attended synagogue worship on the Sabbath. The Lord of the Sabbath honoured the Sabbath.', 11),
  (18, 'ἔχρισέν με', 'echrisen me', 'G5548', 'Hath anointed me — chriō, root of Christos. The reading of Isa 61:1-2 LXX is Jesus''s programmatic "inaugural address" identifying himself as the Messianic Servant.', 12),
  (18, 'εὐαγγελίσασθαι πτωχοῖς', 'euangelisasthai ptōchois', 'G2097/G4434', 'To preach the gospel to the poor — the destitute, the economically and spiritually bankrupt. The Kingdom''s preferential outreach.', 13),
  (18, 'αἰχμαλώτοις ἄφεσιν', 'aichmalōtois aphesin', 'G164/G859', 'Deliverance to the captives — the Jubilee word (Lev 25:10 LXX). Jesus inaugurates the eschatological Jubilee.', 14),
  (19, 'ἐνιαυτὸν κυρίου δεκτόν', 'eniauton kyriou dekton', 'G1763/G2962/G1184', 'The acceptable year of the Lord — Jubilee. Note: Jesus stops mid-sentence in Isa 61:2, omitting "the day of vengeance" — first advent is grace, second advent is judgment.', 15),
  (21, 'πεπλήρωται', 'peplērōtai', 'G4137', 'Is fulfilled — perfect passive of plēroō, "stands fulfilled." Today the Scripture is being fulfilled in your hearing — Jesus claims to be the prophesied Servant.', 16),
  (22, 'λόγοις τῆς χάριτος', 'logois tēs charitos', 'G3056/G5485', 'Words of grace — gracious, winsome speech. The crowd is initially captivated — until Jesus exposes their unbelief in vv.23-27.', 17),
  (23, 'παραβολὴν', 'parabolēn', 'G3850', 'Parable / proverb — "Physician, heal thyself" expresses Nazareth''s scepticism: prove yourself with miracles before we will believe.', 18),
  (25, 'χήραι', 'chērai', 'G5503', 'Widows — Jesus''s deliberately provocative point: in Elijah''s day God bypassed Israel''s widows for a Phoenician widow at Zarephath (1 Kings 17). Sovereign grace transcends ethnic boundary.', 19),
  (27, 'Ναιμὰν ὁ Σύρος', 'Naiman ho Syros', 'G3497/G4948', 'Naaman the Syrian — Elisha cleansed a Gentile leper, not Israel''s many lepers (2 Kings 5). Two OT precedents that infuriate the synagogue: God''s grace reaches Gentiles even when Jews reject it.', 20),
  (29, 'ὀφρύος τοῦ ὄρους', 'ophryos tou orous', 'G3790/G3735', 'Brow of the hill — the cliff of Nazareth. Jesus''s townsfolk attempt to throw him off; the first of many attempts on his life.', 21),
  (30, 'διελθὼν διὰ μέσου αὐτῶν ἐπορεύετο', 'dielthōn dia mesou autōn eporeueto', 'G1330/G3319', 'Passing through the midst of them, went his way — likely a supernatural escape. His hour was not yet come (cf. John 8:59).', 22),
  (32, 'ἐξεπλήσσοντο', 'exeplēssonto', 'G1605', 'Were astonished — imperfect passive, "were being knocked out of their senses." His teaching had inherent authority, not derivative rabbinic citations.', 23),
  (34, 'ὁ ἅγιος τοῦ θεοῦ', 'ho hagios tou theou', 'G40/G2316', 'The Holy One of God — the demon recognises Jesus''s true identity before any human confession (cf. Mark 1:24). Demonic Christology surpasses fleshly perception.', 24),
  (36, 'ἐπιτάσσει', 'epitassei', 'G2004', 'Commandeth — military term for orders. Jesus speaks to demons as a general commanding troops; absolute authority.', 25),
  (39, 'ἐπιτιμήσας', 'epitimēsas', 'G2008', 'Rebuked — same verb used of rebuking demons (4:35,41). Luke the physician describes the fever as if it were a hostile force — disease itself is part of the cosmic disorder Jesus is overturning.', 26),
  (41, 'σὺ εἶ ὁ Χριστὸς', 'sy ei ho Christos', 'G5547', 'Thou art the Christ — demonic confession. Jesus silences them; the timing and content of messianic disclosure must be his.', 27),
  (43, 'ἀπεστάλην', 'apestalēn', 'G649', 'I am sent — aorist passive of apostellō, root of "apostle." Jesus speaks of his divine commission from the Father.', 28),
  (43, 'βασιλείαν τοῦ θεοῦ', 'basileian tou theou', 'G932/G2316', 'Kingdom of God — the central content of Jesus''s preaching. Not a place but God''s royal saving reign breaking in.', 29)
) AS w(verse_number, original_word, transliteration, strongs_number, meaning, word_order)
WHERE b.name = 'Luke' AND c.chapter_number = 4 AND v.verse_number = w.verse_number
ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;

